{"agent_memory": {"title": "ai-bookkeeper: input-hygiene gaps cluster at the categorize/ledger money boundary (prompt-injection + numeric-literal coercion)", "content": "Across two scans (2026-05-27, 2026-06-01), the recurring security theme in ai-bookkeeper is input hygiene at the untrusted money/LLM boundary, not secrets or dep CVEs. Two distinct gap classes: (1) PROMPT INJECTION — the user-controlled `description` at POST /api/categorize is interpolated raw and uncapped into the LLM prompt (parse-request.ts -> categorize.ts buildPrompt); the /api/ask question is capped but still undelimited. (2) NUMERIC-LITERAL COERCION — bare Number() on string amounts accepts JS literals ('1e5'->100000, '0x10'->16, '0b100'->4) at BOTH the live categorize boundary and the parseAmount ledger validator, because stripping only [$,\\s] leaves 'e'/'x'/'b' intact; the fix is a digit-only regex (/^\\d+(\\.\\d{1,2})?$/) before Number(). Business lesson: this codebase's security risk lives at the data-ingestion seams that feed money math and LLM prompts — prioritize boundary-validation there over chasing build-time dep CVEs (the only deps finding, postcss<8.5.10, is dev-only and its npm fix is an unacceptable major next downgrade). The team has already approved a consolidated cap+delimit fix for the description; a single boundary-validation PR could close the description cap + both numeric-coercion sites together.", "category": "learned", "importance": 4, "tags": ["ai-bookkeeper", "security-scan", "prompt-injection", "input-validation", "money-boundary", "categorize", "amount-coercion"]}}

{"knowledge_annotation": {"scope": "global", "note": "JS Number() coercion is a recurring input-validation trap at money boundaries: Number('1e5')=100000, Number('0x10')=16, Number('0b100')=4 all parse to finite in-range values, so a downstream 'is finite / <= max / <=2 decimals' guard (e.g. isValidSignedAmount) does NOT catch them. To reject scientific/hex/binary literals, validate the raw string with a digit-only regex like /^-?\\d+(\\.\\d{1,2})?$/ BEFORE calling Number(). Note Number('1_000')=NaN and Number('Infinity')=Infinity, so those are caught, but the literal forms are not.", "confidence": 0.95}}

